IRS990.Desc: Tree Operations: Initial activities involve the community outreach and engagement associated with finding new tree installation locations. Location strategy is in direct relation to the lack of investment in communities and lack of canopy coverage of said neighborhoods. Procurement, installation, maintenance, pruning, and tracking of trees are fundamental to the Tree Operations Department scope of work.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: Casey Tree Farm: Activities geared toward the production of trees and strengthening of Casey Trees' support network.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: Communications & Development: The Communications and Development department connects people to trees, through trees, and to Casey Trees. The department achieves this by providing high-quality content, memorable experiences, outstanding customer service, and expanding the organization's support network. They complete activities that disseminate information about Casey Trees to encourage engagement in, and broad support, of its work.

ProgSrvcAccomActyOtherGrp.Desc: Education: Activities associated with the development, implementation and evaluation of tree-based education and training programs.
Policy & Land Conservation: Promotes tree-friendly urban design, preservation of land, and community action in support of our mission

Form990ScheduleAPartVIGrp.ExplanationTxt: Two members of the governing body of the Garden Club of America (the supported organization) also serve as members of the governing body of Casey Trees (the supporting organization). The President of the Garden Club of America ("GCA") annually appoints two members of the Board of Directors of the GCA to serve on Casey Trees' Board of Directors. Both members are chosen from the membership of the GCA. Service as a director of Casey Trees shall automatically terminate in the event such director is no longer a member of the GCA, for any reason whatsoever.

The mission of the GCA is to stimulate the knowledge and love of gardening, to share the advantages of assocation by means of educational meetings, conferences, correspondence, and pubclications, and to restore, improve, and protect the quality of the environment through educational programs and action in the fields of conservation and civic improvement. Substantially all Casey Trees activities conducted are in direct furtherance of the mission of the GCA. Casey Trees was organized by the GCA in 2001 to accept a permanently restricted endowment granted by the Eugene B. Casey Foundation of Gaithersburg, Maryland. Casey Trees provides support to the GCA through its reforestation projects in Washington, D.C.
Casey Trees holds title to and manages exempt use assets through its ownership of Casey Tree Farm, LLC. Casey Trees activities include tree planting and the protection of the "Urban Canopy".

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Line 1a: Volunteers are trained to be advocates in their community, trained to provide testimony to Council Members and stakeholders, and trained on the role of tree legislation in DC. Line 1b: Staff train volunteers and periodically meet with DC stakeholders including public officials to emphasize the importance of trees in our community. Line 1d: Email communications Line 1g: Casey Trees staff have periodic meetings with DC officials and provide testimony for the City Council hearings on potential legislation and its impacts on the mission of Casey Trees. We also issue calls to action through our online newsletter.

The conservation agreements and related documents state that Casey Trees maintains the following rights with regard to monitoring and enforcement policies: 1. A perpetual easement and right to preserve and protect the conservation values of the property; 2. A perpetual easement and right to enter upon and inspect the property at reasonable times, and upon prior reasonable notice in order to monitor the landowner's compliance with and otherwise enforce the terms of the easement; provided, however, in cases where holder determines that immediate entry is reasonably necessary to prevent, terminate or mitigate a violation or suspected violation of this conservation easement, such entry may be without prior notice to land owner. 3. A perpetual easement and right to prevent (including the right to see injunctive relief) for any activity on or use of the property that is inconsistent with terms of the conservation easement and the purpose, and to require restoration of such areas or features of the property that may be damaged by any inconsistent activity or use; and 4. A perpetual easement and right to display on the property, at its discretion such signs as it may customarily use to identify lands under conservation easement, the terms of the conservation easement or the conservation values being protected. If Casey Trees determines that the landowner, or third parties under landowner's authority or control or acting with landowner's knowledge, is in violation of the terms of the conservation easement, Casey Trees will give written notice to landowner of such violations and demand corrective action. If landowner fails to cure the violation within 30 days after receipt of notice, Casey Trees may bring action at law or in equity in a court of competent jurisdiction to enforce terms of the conservation easement.

The Organization is a holder and administrator of five conservation easements in various locations in Washington, D.C. The purpose of the conservation easements is to preserve and protect the environment of the properties and permanently maintain the open-space value and character of the associated property. The conservation easements held by the Organization were all obtained via gift deed from the property owner of record at the time of donation. Since these easements have no marketable value, the Organization assigned a nominal value of $1 per easement and included them in other assets in the accompanying consolidated statements of financial position. The conservation easements totaled $5 at year end.
Casey Trees' endowment is used to fund operations.
Management has evaluated the Organization's tax positions and concluded that the Organization had no significant uncertain tax positions at June 30, 2023 and 2022.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 12c
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: In connection with any actual or possible conflict of interest, an interested person must disclose the existence of the interest as soon as s/he realizes a conflict of interest exists to the Executive Committee of the Board of Directors or a governing body established by the Board President. After exercising due diligence with all the information available to it, the Executive Committee or governing board shall determine whether Casey Trees can obtain with reasonable efforts a more advantageous transaction or arrangement from a person or entity that would not give rise to a conflict of interest. If not, the Executive Committee or governing board shall determine by a majority vote whether the transaction or arrangement is in Casey Trees' best interest, for its own benefit, and whether it is fair and reasonable. In conformity with the above determination it shall make its decision as to whether to enter into the transaction or arrangment. A record of the aformentioned proceedings shall be kept that identifies the person(s) with the potential conflict of interest, the nature of the conflict itself, the names of the members of the committee present for deliberations, and the nature of the discussion and resolution(s). Failure to report a conflict of interest may result in disciplinary action including termination.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 15
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: When hiring an Executive Director, the Board President shall review documents pertaining to the cash and non-cash compensation for Executive Directors of similar organizations to determine if the compensation package is appropriate. Setting of the initial salary level will account for skills, experience, locality adjustments, etc. Thereafter, on an annual basis, the Board President will review the Executive Director's performance, and account for factors such as internal and external pay equity and others as appropriate, to determine if a salary increase or other compensation is warranted. The President may assign this duty to another board member(s) at his/her discretion as needs dictate. The setting of the initial salary/benefit levels, and any increases, shall be reviewed and agreed to by the Executive Committee of the Board.
